        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: The fear of espionage forces Danish universities to reject foreign students from Russia and China.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Denmark is tightening security in its universities, rejecting some foreign students over concerns they could <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-18-jul-25-spotlights-h2-6-pass-on-sensitive-research?source=website" target="_blank">pass on sensitive research</a> to their governments. They are particularly concerned about researchers from Russia, Iran, and China, who want to work in fields such as quantum technology and green energy. Aarhus University alone rejected at least 24 applicants from these countries. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>The background:</strong> Denmarkâ€™s strong position in green technology and Arctic research has attracted foreign interest. Intelligence officials warn that some states try to gain information on the Arctic and North Atlantic regions, negotiations, and key individuals by pressuring or recruiting researchers through bribes and blackmail (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-18-jul-25-spotlights-h2-7-espionage-in-denmark?source=website" target="_blank">espionage in Denmark</a>). 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>The big picture:</strong> These stricter rules come as Denmark takes on the rotating EU presidency. 
         Universities are relying on staff and outside experts to screen applicants, mostly in natural and health sciences. While seen as vital for security, the policy risks slowing international research collaboration.
          </p>
