          <strong>The what:</strong> Once praised as a model of postâ€‘Soviet democracy, Georgia is drifting away from the West. Its government has embraced <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-18-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-anti-western-rhetoric?source=website" target="_blank">antiâ€‘Western rhetoric</a> by awarding contracts to Chinese stateâ€‘linked companies and helping Iran bypass sanctions. At the same time, efforts to join the EU have stalled, raising alarm in Brussels and Washington about Moscowâ€™s growing influence.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The reaction:</strong> In response, the US is pushing to pass the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-18-07-2025-megobari-act?source=website" target="_blank">Megobari Act</a>, which would allow sanctions, visa bans, and asset freezes on Georgian officials involved in election fraud, corruption, or political crackdowns. However, analysts suggest that outside pressure is unlikely to change Georgiaâ€™s course as its leaders are systematically shutting down opposition.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>On the ground:</strong> The ruling Georgian Dream Party currently controls all branches of government and has <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-18-jul-25-analysis-h2-9-arrested-many-opposition-figures?source=website" target="_blank">arrested many opposition figures</a>. People are protesting against the government over authoritarian concerns for almost 200 days, wearing masks to prevent detection by Chinese-made facial recognition cameras. 
