        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>The Big Three, however, also had to make decisions about the stabilization of China, Axis satellite states, and orderly population transfers. Credits: Wikimedia Commons</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The what:</strong> <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-18-jul-25-foundations-h1-15-the-potsdam-conference?source=website" target="_blank">The Potsdam Conference</a> was a critical Allied meeting from July 17 to August 2, 1945, near Berlin. Leaders, including Harry S. Truman (US), Clement Attlee (UK), and Joseph Stalin (Soviet Union), attended the conference. They discussed concerns about handling a defeated Germany, the fate of Poland, and the final destruction of Japanese military power. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        <strong>The resolution:</strong> The Allies decided to divide Germany into four occupation zones and planned reparations, mainly for the Soviet Union. In exchange for the land lost by Poland, they were compensated in the west with large areas in Germany, along the border of the Rivers Oder and Neisse. Additionally, they called for Japan's unconditional surrender. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>The disagreement:</strong> There were disputes over the future of Eastern Europe. Stalin wanted control over neighboring countries. Truman, aware of the atomic bomb's power, took a firmer stance. The tensions at Potsdam underscored the growing divide between the Soviet Union and the Western Allies, serving as a catalyst for the onset of the Cold War. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
